!! How the IIFE bundle is loaded

mind-elixir's `MindElixir.iife.js` is a self-executing function that, when evaluated, declares `var MindElixir = (function(W){...})({})` in the surrounding scope. TW's `require()` evaluates module text inside a closure that already has `module`, `exports`, `require` in scope; our trailer (`module.exports = MindElixir`) captures the local variable and re-exports it.

This is why the `.meta` says `module-type: library` — it makes the file `require()`-able by the adapter without TW trying to interpret it as a widget or filter operator.

!! Function-name override for engine discovery

The host widget's `findEngineByName(name)` iterates registered `mindmapengine` modules and matches against `exports.name`. Our adapter exports a constructor function. JavaScript's `Function.prototype.name` is configurable in ES2015+, so we use `Object.defineProperty(Engine, "name", { value: "MindElixir" })` rather than direct assignment (which can silently fail in strict mode).

!! mind-elixir mutates input data

`me.init(data)` and `me.refresh(data)` both mutate the `data.nodeData` tree (mind-elixir attaches DOM references and internal flags). The adapter therefore deep-clones the composite MDOM before each call. Failing to clone would corrupt the host widget's cached composite and break orphan detection on the next change.

!! Global keyboard listeners

mind-elixir attaches `keydown` and `keyup` listeners on `document` when `keypress: true` (default). The adapter relies on mind-elixir's own `destroy()` method to release them; we wrap the call in try/catch since some versions throw if destroy is called without a prior init.

!! TW auto-`<p>` wrapping

`<$mindmap>` rendered via `<$transclude $mode="block">` may be wrapped in `<p>`. Our parent plugin's `styles.tid` includes `.rr-mindmap > p { display: contents }` to neutralise this, matching the cytoscape-engine pattern.

!! Restricted-wiki environments

Overlay writes go through the host widget's `overlay-store` and target the view's `mm.overlay` tiddler. If `llm-connect`-style restricted wiki blocks writes to that title, the adapter cannot detect the failure client-side. Document in your view's setup which overlay titles are in the allow filter.

</$fill>
